      <p>Buying cycle reality: 2–8 week reorder by pet size and product type; life-stage transitions. Email cadence must respect that rhythm — not the marketing calendar alone.</p>
      <p>Implementation: audit consent sources in week one, launch welcome segmented by source in week two, add cart or post-purchase in week three, measure repeat purchase movement in week four.</p>
      <p>Peak season for pet product stores requires pausing non-essential flows, protecting VIP segments, and aligning merchandising with inbox promises — governance matters more than new app installs.</p>
      <p>Deliverability note: pet product stores with aggressive promos need authentication, frequency caps, and sunset policies — complaint spikes often trace to offer mismatch, not weak templates.</p>
      <p>Pair capture tools (Privy, Justuno) only when list growth is the leak; pair Postscript when SMS recovery justifies cost. Avoid three senders without a collision calendar.</p>
      <p>Read comparisons and use-case playbooks on this site for head-to-head tradeoffs and execution detail specific to pet lifecycle, reorder timing, and product education.</p>
